WEBVTT

00:17.240 --> 00:19.280
NARRATOR: Although not
officially declared an orphan

00:19.280 --> 00:21.680
until her 10th birthday,

00:21.680 --> 00:24.040
Matilda Stone lost her mother

00:24.040 --> 00:26.880
three days,
three hours, and three minutes

00:26.880 --> 00:29.120
into her third year.

00:30.920 --> 00:34.000
She would later tell of feeling
the invisible cord

00:34.000 --> 00:38.000
all children share with their
mother suddenly snapping...

00:39.760 --> 00:42.200
...and of how,
even at the tender age

00:42.200 --> 00:43.760
of three years, three days,

00:43.760 --> 00:47.040
three hours,
and three minutes old,

00:47.040 --> 00:51.880
she was sure she would never
see her mother alive again.

00:51.880 --> 00:54.720
[ Caws ]

00:54.720 --> 00:57.960
Despite the tragedy,
Matilda grew up well cared for

00:57.960 --> 01:02.080
and well loved by her mother's
three crime-writing sisters --

01:02.080 --> 01:02.880
Jane...

01:02.880 --> 01:04.120
Study hard.

01:04.120 --> 01:05.760
...Cat...

01:05.760 --> 01:09.920
Remember -- Anyone starts, make
sure you land the first punch.

01:09.920 --> 01:12.040
...and Beth Stone.

01:12.040 --> 01:15.040
Tuna pasta bake --
your favorite.

01:18.440 --> 01:20.880
Moving regularly between aunts,

01:20.880 --> 01:23.400
Matilda especially enjoyed
living above

01:23.400 --> 01:27.840
her Aunt Jane's
crime bookshop, Murder Ink.

01:30.320 --> 01:32.840
At night, she would
sneak downstairs,

01:32.840 --> 01:37.800
take a book at random, and read
by torchlight until dawn.

01:37.800 --> 01:39.280
From Allingham to Zimler,

01:39.280 --> 01:41.280
and every author in between,

01:41.280 --> 01:44.000
Matilda's childhood
was spent devouring

01:44.000 --> 01:47.440
her aunt's library
of crime fiction.

01:47.440 --> 01:51.720
So it was no surprise when,
aged 18,

01:51.720 --> 01:54.240
Matilda left her childhood home
of Wildemarsh

01:54.240 --> 01:56.080
to join the police.

01:56.080 --> 01:57.800
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

01:57.800 --> 02:00.600
However, the mystery
of her mother's disappearance

02:00.600 --> 02:02.200
never left her.

02:02.200 --> 02:05.240
How and why she vanished,
and who -- if anyone --

02:05.240 --> 02:08.639
was responsible,
has never been established.

02:08.639 --> 02:10.639
And as Matilda
returned to Wildemarsh

02:10.639 --> 02:13.160
in her mother's beloved car,

02:13.160 --> 02:17.640
she pondered the few
known facts of the case --

02:17.640 --> 02:20.080
The haiku
scribbled in her mother's hand

02:20.080 --> 02:22.480
on the blackboard
of Matilda's nursery.

02:24.320 --> 02:27.200
The smoldering Bulgarian
cigarette found in the ashtray

02:27.200 --> 02:29.040
of her mother's car.

02:29.040 --> 02:31.520
The solitary black feather

02:31.520 --> 02:34.960
discovered in her
mother's safe deposit box.

02:37.280 --> 02:40.840
All of these things might
or might not be connected...

02:42.720 --> 02:46.800
...or may or may not lead
to the solving of the riddle

02:46.800 --> 02:51.240
that has haunted Matilda
since childhood.

02:51.240 --> 02:55.600
A riddle she one day
hopes to solve.

03:09.120 --> 03:10.560
[ Caws ]

04:40.560 --> 04:42.600
Matilda Stone
reporting for duty.

04:42.600 --> 04:43.440
Matilda!

04:45.480 --> 04:46.320
Terry Foster.

04:47.440 --> 04:50.160
You were friends
with my sister Kate.

04:50.160 --> 04:52.400
It had been 12 years,
two months,

04:52.400 --> 04:54.680
three days, and 16 hours

04:54.680 --> 04:56.320
since Police Constable Foster

04:56.320 --> 04:59.040
first laid eyes
on Matilda Stone,

04:59.040 --> 05:01.920
and the flame ignited
by that first encounter

05:01.920 --> 05:04.400
still burned bright.

05:04.400 --> 05:07.160
I'm sorry,
I don't remember.

05:07.160 --> 05:10.040
No.
No, no, no, c-course not.

05:10.040 --> 05:12.000
[ Chuckles nervously ]
There's no reason for you to.

05:13.280 --> 05:15.640
So, uh...

05:17.560 --> 05:20.280
It's P.C. Foster now, anyways.

05:22.080 --> 05:24.240
-And you're...?
-Detective sergeant.

05:24.240 --> 05:26.800
Which means I'll be
working under you.

05:26.800 --> 05:28.960
Beneath you!

05:28.960 --> 05:29.840
Withyou.

05:31.680 --> 05:33.600
Well, I'd better
get the inspector.

05:37.560 --> 05:39.520
You're late, Stone.
My office.

05:55.680 --> 05:57.520
Don't sit.

05:57.520 --> 05:58.960
I won't lie, Sergeant.

05:58.960 --> 06:00.560
You weren't my first choice
for this position.

06:00.560 --> 06:03.200
In fact
you weren't in my top 10.

06:03.200 --> 06:06.040
Now, I see you were born
in Wildemarsh.

06:06.040 --> 06:08.160
Yes, sir.
My aunts brought me up.

06:08.160 --> 06:10.160
-The Stone sisters?
-You know them?

06:10.160 --> 06:12.520
They've offered me
their services.

06:12.520 --> 06:14.240
-Writing?
-Detecting.

06:14.240 --> 06:16.360
I'm sure
they only meant the best.

06:16.360 --> 06:18.280
You shouldn't need me
to tell you, Sergeant --

06:18.280 --> 06:20.720
There's no place for the amateur
sleuth in modern policing.

06:20.720 --> 06:24.440
What Inspector Thorne
wanted to say next was...

06:24.440 --> 06:28.760
I've loved your Aunt Jane
from afar for 25 years,

06:28.760 --> 06:30.400
and I can't bring myself
to be near her

06:30.400 --> 06:33.120
for fear of
making a fool of myself.

06:33.120 --> 06:35.920
But what he chose to say was...

06:35.920 --> 06:38.600
We're the police,
and under no circumstances

06:38.600 --> 06:41.000
do we require the help
of three meddling aunts.

06:41.000 --> 06:43.040
-Do I make myself clear?
-Perfectly, sir.

06:43.040 --> 06:45.440
Unpack your things.
Your shift starts in 15 minutes.

06:45.440 --> 06:47.760
But Aunt Beth's been nominated
for an award,

06:47.760 --> 06:49.320
and I was hoping...

06:50.880 --> 06:52.440
I'll go unpack.

06:54.320 --> 06:56.080
The award in question

06:56.080 --> 06:58.560
was the prestigious
Golden Pick-Axe

06:58.560 --> 07:01.560
for best crime writer
of the year...

07:04.440 --> 07:06.800
...the culmination
of Hiddledean Castle's

07:06.800 --> 07:10.440
15th Wildemarsh
Crime Writers' Festival...

07:11.840 --> 07:15.520
...an annual celebration
of crime fiction

07:15.520 --> 07:17.640
and a place
where the great and the good

07:17.640 --> 07:20.240
of the crime-writing world
get the opportunity

07:20.240 --> 07:22.000
to meet their fans...

07:23.680 --> 07:25.280
...and promote their wares.

07:31.080 --> 07:33.080
Although Beth Stone's series

07:33.080 --> 07:35.080
following the criminal
investigations

07:35.080 --> 07:37.720
of inner-city vicar
Iris Freeman

07:37.720 --> 07:41.120
were the most successful
of the three sisters' novels...

07:43.760 --> 07:47.040
...Cat Stone's acclaimed
Roxanne Parker graphic novels

07:47.040 --> 07:49.880
about a kick-ass
music-industry fixer...

07:52.720 --> 07:56.200
...and Jane Stone's
offbeat Henry Lambert books

07:56.200 --> 07:59.520
about an android
police detective

07:59.520 --> 08:02.120
were more than able
to hold their own

08:02.120 --> 08:05.440
in such exalted company.

08:05.440 --> 08:07.320
Oh, I do hope you win.

08:07.320 --> 08:09.640
Well, it's an honor
just to be nominated.

08:09.640 --> 08:11.600
[ Chuckles ]
Said the loser.

08:11.600 --> 08:14.160
Besides, the smart money's

08:14.160 --> 08:16.080
on the reclusive
Benjamin Kingston.

08:17.280 --> 08:20.080
Rumor has it Lady H. has
promised him the Golden Pick-Axe

08:20.080 --> 08:21.640
just for turning up
to the festival.

08:21.640 --> 08:22.840
Can she do that?

08:22.840 --> 08:24.720
Well, who do you think
picks the winner?

08:24.720 --> 08:26.080
[ Sighs ]

08:29.440 --> 08:32.200
And it is in
this exalted company

08:32.200 --> 08:34.120
that the cash-strapped founder

08:34.120 --> 08:36.640
of the Wildemarsh
Crime Writers' Festival

08:36.640 --> 08:39.120
and eponymous owner
of Hiddledean Castle,

08:39.120 --> 08:42.440
Lady Antonia...Hiddledean,

08:42.440 --> 08:45.560
once again finds herself
hosting a Q and A

08:45.560 --> 08:48.360
with this year's
Golden Pick-Axe Award nominees.

08:48.360 --> 08:50.760
HIDDLEDEAN:
Our esteemed authors --

08:50.760 --> 08:53.320
Oscar Prescott...

08:55.640 --> 08:57.760
...Isabella Wolfe...

09:02.040 --> 09:04.520
...Benjamin Kingston...

09:05.880 --> 09:07.200
...and last but not least,

09:07.200 --> 09:12.520
Wildemarsh's very own
Beth Stone.

09:12.520 --> 09:14.360
I'm sure the audience
would love to know

09:14.360 --> 09:18.040
how you get your ideas
for your novels.

09:20.480 --> 09:22.600
Maybe you should take this one,
Isabella.

09:22.600 --> 09:25.720
I mean, I for one,
I would be fascinated to learn

09:25.720 --> 09:28.440
how you came up with the idea
for your latest novel.

09:28.440 --> 09:31.000
What's it called again?
"Death on the High Seas"?

09:31.000 --> 09:34.640
[ Clears throat ] It's --
It's "Murder on the Mary Rose."

09:34.640 --> 09:36.320
You don't sound sure.

09:36.320 --> 09:39.720
Well, to answer
your original question,

09:39.720 --> 09:41.640
it came to me in a flash.

09:41.640 --> 09:43.840
Came to you in an envelope
with your name on it, more like.

09:43.840 --> 09:46.800
Oh, well, why don't you
tell us a bit

09:46.800 --> 09:49.600
about your inspiration, Oscar.

09:49.600 --> 09:53.080
Now, how many Charlie Palmer
novels have there been?

09:53.080 --> 09:54.960
-Is it 21?
-It's 23.

09:54.960 --> 09:56.520
HIDDLEDEAN:
Oh, 23, how marvelous.

09:56.520 --> 10:00.400
As my slightly overenthusiastic
assistant correctly states,

10:00.400 --> 10:01.800
there have been...

10:04.840 --> 10:07.480
...23, and this...

10:08.920 --> 10:12.680
..."Brown Bread,"
is soon to be number 24.

10:12.680 --> 10:13.560
Oh!

10:15.400 --> 10:18.720
PRESCOTT:
Yeah, yeah, it's, um --

10:18.720 --> 10:20.800
it's based
on a real-life incident that,

10:20.800 --> 10:24.520
coincidentally enough, happened
right here at Hiddledean Castle.

10:24.520 --> 10:27.360
And it's your mother
I have to thank for it, Antonia.

10:27.360 --> 10:29.360
If the baroness
hadn't given me access

10:29.360 --> 10:32.000
to your excellent library
last summer,

10:32.000 --> 10:33.880
I should have never uncovered
the story.

10:33.880 --> 10:35.560
WOMAN:
What's it about, Oscar?

10:35.560 --> 10:38.840
Uh, sorry, sorry, but my agent,

10:38.840 --> 10:40.240
who's sitting right there...

10:41.840 --> 10:43.960
...has given me
strict instructions

10:43.960 --> 10:46.160
not to discuss the plot

10:46.160 --> 10:47.040
until I deliver
the manuscript.

10:47.040 --> 10:48.040
-Sorry.
-[ Audience groans ]

10:48.040 --> 10:50.720
No, no, we must respect

10:50.720 --> 10:52.520
an author's right
to privacy.

10:52.520 --> 10:53.360
Please, Oscar.

10:56.680 --> 10:58.200
Well, all right,
I suppose I can tell you

10:58.200 --> 10:59.720
a little bit about it.

10:59.720 --> 11:04.280
So, it's 1963.
It's the Summer of Love.

11:04.280 --> 11:07.480
Every new novel about
Cockney gumshoe Charlie Palmer

11:07.480 --> 11:08.720
created a literary buzz.

11:08.720 --> 11:11.800
...stately home of hippie
aristocrat Baron Tollage,

11:11.800 --> 11:13.400
where our hero, Charlie Palmer,

11:13.400 --> 11:15.760
is caught up in a case
involving the baron

11:15.760 --> 11:18.920
and his current crop
of sycophants and hangers-on.

11:18.920 --> 11:22.720
And this latest installment
was no exception.

11:22.720 --> 11:25.840
48 hours earlier,
a stray bullet,

11:25.840 --> 11:28.440
originally destined for the
heart of an unwitting pigeon...

11:28.440 --> 11:29.520
[ Gunshot ]

11:29.520 --> 11:31.200
...found itself
embedded in the neck

11:31.200 --> 11:33.480
of an entirely
different quarry...

11:35.320 --> 11:36.880
...Baron Tollage's chum...

11:36.880 --> 11:38.240
[ Bullet ricochets ]

11:38.240 --> 11:40.680
...Lord Grint.

11:40.680 --> 11:42.560
PALMER: [ Cockney accent ] I'm
like one of them pigs

11:42.560 --> 11:44.720
our French cousins use
to find truffles.

11:44.720 --> 11:46.480
I get me nose dirty.

11:46.480 --> 11:48.240
PRESCOTT: Everyone thought
Lord Grint's death

11:48.240 --> 11:49.960
was an unfortunate accident,

11:49.960 --> 11:52.440
but Charlie's investigations
led him to conclude

11:52.440 --> 11:53.880
that he was in fact...

11:53.880 --> 11:55.480
PALMER:
...murdered by someone...

11:55.480 --> 11:56.680
...in this very room.

11:56.680 --> 11:58.800
Oh, I'm so sorry!

11:58.800 --> 12:01.120
Oh, gosh, I really am sorry,
but I'm afraid --

12:01.120 --> 12:04.000
I hate to interrupt you when
you're in full flow, Oscar --

12:04.000 --> 12:05.200
no, do believe me,
I really do --

12:05.200 --> 12:07.120
but I'm afraid
we've run out of time.

12:07.120 --> 12:10.240
So why don't we show
our appreciation

12:10.240 --> 12:13.840
to our four
Golden Pick-Axe nominees.

12:13.840 --> 12:15.760
[ Audience cheering ]

12:15.760 --> 12:19.240
Bravo and four hurrahs
to -- to all of you.

12:19.240 --> 12:22.040
Now, we have
the award presentation

12:22.040 --> 12:23.680
at 7:00 this evening,

12:23.680 --> 12:25.560
and I am very much
looking forward to you

12:25.560 --> 12:27.720
all joining me there.

12:27.720 --> 12:29.080
Thank you so much.

12:40.400 --> 12:42.600
Tobias Young --
Benjamin Kingston's agent.

12:42.600 --> 12:44.000
I'm a guest of the festival.

12:44.000 --> 12:45.800
Would you mind signing in?

12:45.800 --> 12:48.760
Although blessed with
good health and good looks,

12:48.760 --> 12:51.400
literary agent Tobias Young

12:51.400 --> 12:56.600
had considerably less luck
in other areas of his life.

12:56.600 --> 13:00.960
Luck that, if nothing else,
was at least consistent.

13:00.960 --> 13:03.160
[ Man laughs ]

13:05.280 --> 13:09.560
Oh, and if anyone asks,
I'm not here.

13:09.560 --> 13:11.520
ASHTON: Well, there was
a mini bar last year.

13:11.520 --> 13:13.000
It's very disappointing.

13:16.280 --> 13:18.600
Hello, Guy Ashton.
There's a phone call for me.

13:18.600 --> 13:20.040
Yes, Mr. Ashton.

13:22.240 --> 13:24.000
Thank you.

13:24.000 --> 13:25.560
-Hello, John.
-Guy.

13:25.560 --> 13:27.400
Yes, sorry, my battery ran out.

13:27.400 --> 13:28.760
Has he signed?

13:28.760 --> 13:32.440
No, no, Oscar hasn't signed
the contract yet.

13:32.440 --> 13:34.880
I showed it to him, and he told
me where to stick it. [ Snorts ]

13:34.880 --> 13:37.720
Well, Guy, we really need
to move this forward,

13:37.720 --> 13:38.840
You know that.

13:38.840 --> 13:40.560
No, I know.
I know time's running out.

13:40.560 --> 13:42.680
I want it on my desk
first thing tomorrow morning.

13:42.680 --> 13:44.200
-Yes. Well...
-[ Device beeping ]

13:44.200 --> 13:46.680
No more delay.
Do you understand me, Guy?

13:46.680 --> 13:48.840
-As soon as it's done.
-[ Beeping accelerates ]

13:52.400 --> 13:54.760
Ah!
[ Breathing heavily ]

13:56.920 --> 13:58.000
[ Beeping stops ]

14:02.120 --> 14:05.680
Your coffee --
Can I have it, please?

14:05.680 --> 14:07.000
Thank you.

14:10.560 --> 14:11.560
[ Exhales sharply ]

14:15.880 --> 14:17.560
You're very kind.

14:27.560 --> 14:29.680
-Is everything okay, Mr. Young?
-You know what?

14:31.520 --> 14:33.080
I think it's going to be.

14:36.360 --> 14:38.240
"To my dear friend, Cat,

14:38.240 --> 14:41.120
who stuck by me
through thick and thin."

14:41.120 --> 14:43.040
[ Chuckles ]

14:43.040 --> 14:45.600
And just how thick arethings?

14:45.600 --> 14:48.480
Half a million in sales, three
weeks at the top of the charts

14:48.480 --> 14:50.440
and a Golden Pick-Axe
nomination.

14:50.440 --> 14:53.360
-And they said I was finished.
-You were.

14:57.080 --> 14:58.440
You haven't seen Beth,
have you?

14:58.440 --> 14:59.640
No.

14:59.640 --> 15:00.920
[ Horn honks ]

15:06.720 --> 15:07.760
[ Car door closes ]

15:09.760 --> 15:12.040
Isabella!

15:14.480 --> 15:15.760
Max!

15:15.760 --> 15:17.040
-Ha ha! Mwah!
-Mwah! Mwah!

15:18.240 --> 15:19.800
Aren't you going to
introduce me?

15:19.800 --> 15:22.760
Cat, Maximilian Sinclair,
Sinclair Publishing.

15:22.760 --> 15:24.920
Max, Cat Stone.

15:24.920 --> 15:27.040
I had a poster of your band
on my wall

15:27.040 --> 15:29.240
throughout my formative years.

15:29.240 --> 15:31.120
You must have been
a very late developer.

15:31.120 --> 15:33.560
-SINCLAIR: [ Laughs ]
-What are you doing here, Max?

15:33.560 --> 15:35.920
I thought you hated
literary festivals.

15:35.920 --> 15:38.720
I do. You wouldn't catch me dead
at one of these dreary events.

15:38.720 --> 15:42.120
But Oscar insisted I attend.

15:42.120 --> 15:45.480
And, well, when your
best-selling author says jump,

15:45.480 --> 15:49.160
a humble publisher can only ask,
"How high?"

15:49.160 --> 15:50.680
[ Laughs ]

15:52.360 --> 15:54.800
But we'd agreed
you were gonna sign today.

15:54.800 --> 15:59.000
Yeah, well, you know, I need
more time to think about it.

15:59.000 --> 16:01.240
I don't have more time.

16:02.960 --> 16:04.200
I've made promises to people.

16:05.640 --> 16:07.480
I assume you're talking about
the people who bust your arm?

16:08.880 --> 16:11.120
How much do you owe them
this time?

16:11.120 --> 16:14.680
Look, I've been with Guy
since Cambridge.

16:14.680 --> 16:17.600
The least I can do is offer him
a chance to improve his terms.

16:17.600 --> 16:19.240
Whatever they are,
I'll beat them.

16:20.440 --> 16:21.360
-I know.
-[ Ball clacks ]

16:34.520 --> 16:35.360
CAT: Beth?

16:40.400 --> 16:43.280
The figures are correct.
I've had them verified.

16:44.560 --> 16:45.920
So...

16:48.080 --> 16:50.120
What do you want?

16:50.120 --> 16:52.560
I'm making some changes
to my life, Max.

16:52.560 --> 16:54.160
Taking back control.

16:54.160 --> 16:55.400
[ Footsteps ]

16:56.560 --> 16:57.800
Oh. Sorry.

17:03.280 --> 17:05.119
Beth?

17:10.359 --> 17:12.720
HIDDLEDEAN: Take them down
as soon as you can.

17:12.720 --> 17:15.119
-Very good, m'lady.
-And then you can feed the dogs.

17:15.119 --> 17:16.520
Oh!
Everything okay, Benjamin?

17:16.520 --> 17:18.119
I'm looking for Emily.

17:18.119 --> 17:20.400
Oscar's P.A.?
Well, she's around somewhere.

17:20.400 --> 17:22.440
Find Oscar,
and you'll find Emily.

17:25.760 --> 17:28.040
You'd be nothing without me,
you ungrateful cur!

17:28.040 --> 17:29.160
I made you!

17:29.160 --> 17:30.680
So I should
just blindly accept

17:30.680 --> 17:33.040
whatever miserly terms
you see fit to impose?

17:33.040 --> 17:34.600
-Yes!
-[ Beeping ]

17:34.600 --> 17:36.560
-[ Gasping ]
-Oh.

17:36.560 --> 17:38.280
-Oh, for God's sake.
-Tablets.

17:38.280 --> 17:40.400
-[ Beeping continues ]
-Yes, yes.

17:40.400 --> 17:42.440
Give it to me, give it to me,
give it to me.

17:44.880 --> 17:47.680
-See what you've done?
-It's hardly my bloody fault.

17:47.680 --> 17:48.960
S-S-Steady on, Oscar.

17:48.960 --> 17:50.840
"S-S-Steady on, Oscar."

17:50.840 --> 17:52.240
You've not changed,
have you, Benji?

17:52.240 --> 17:53.680
Always standing up
for the little people.

17:53.680 --> 17:55.200
-Oscar, are you busy?
-Oh...

17:55.200 --> 17:57.840
Back off, Tobias!
Oscar's my client.

17:57.840 --> 17:59.160
-I just --
-Not now, Tobias.

17:59.160 --> 18:02.800
-Look, I need --
-I said not now! God!

18:02.800 --> 18:06.120
You people are killing me
with your constant demands.

18:06.120 --> 18:08.720
I'll be glad when I'm free
of the lot of you.

18:08.720 --> 18:11.440
Little did
Oscar Prescott realize,

18:11.440 --> 18:14.640
his words had never been
more prophetic.

18:17.280 --> 18:20.440
[ Applause ]

18:23.600 --> 18:25.760
Thank you!
Thank you!

18:25.760 --> 18:28.360
Did you find out
where Beth's been hiding?

18:28.360 --> 18:31.000
I looked everywhere. This is
the first I've seen of her.

18:31.000 --> 18:35.320
Thank you so much,
and a very warm welcome to all.

18:35.320 --> 18:39.080
Welcome to
the Golden Pick-Axe

18:39.080 --> 18:41.520
crime writer of the year award,

18:41.520 --> 18:44.800
and this year's winner is...

18:46.240 --> 18:47.560
[ Inhales sharply ]

18:50.440 --> 18:52.680
[ Inhales sharply ]

19:02.520 --> 19:05.160
...Oscar Prescott!

19:05.160 --> 19:07.360
-[ Cheers and applause ]
-For "Trouble and Strife."

19:07.360 --> 19:08.640
Oh, congratulations.

19:08.640 --> 19:10.840
Oh, bravo.

19:10.840 --> 19:13.080
No one saw that coming.

19:14.560 --> 19:15.840
Oh, congratulations.

19:15.840 --> 19:18.440
Thank you, sweetie.
Thank you, thank you.

19:18.520 --> 19:19.840
Never mind.

19:23.400 --> 19:27.640
Really.
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

19:27.640 --> 19:29.840
Wow! Ah...

19:29.840 --> 19:31.560
Well, look, traditionally,

19:31.560 --> 19:35.000
the winner at this point
would probably make a speech,

19:35.000 --> 19:38.240
but I've never really
been one for tradition,

19:38.240 --> 19:42.000
so instead
I'd like to perform a reading

19:42.000 --> 19:44.440
from the last few pages

19:44.440 --> 19:49.080
of my next Charlie Palmer
mystery, "Brown Bread."

19:49.080 --> 19:50.960
[ Audience murmuring ]

19:53.800 --> 19:56.000
The last few pages?

19:56.000 --> 19:58.600
Won't that rather give away
who did it?

20:00.400 --> 20:02.080
[ Clears throat ]

20:05.240 --> 20:07.760
"Every member of
the shooting party had a motive

20:07.760 --> 20:09.480
to kill Lord Grint,

20:09.480 --> 20:13.120
and Charlie Palmer had spent
the past 24 hours determining

20:13.120 --> 20:15.520
which of them, if any..."

20:15.520 --> 20:17.480
Get Oscar.
I need Oscar.

20:17.480 --> 20:19.960
"...but also the opportunity
to do so."

20:19.960 --> 20:20.960
[ Clears throat ]
Oscar.

20:20.960 --> 20:23.560
"Palmer coolly turned

20:23.560 --> 20:27.080
to take in the guests'
expectant faces and declared,

20:27.080 --> 20:28.680
'The murderer is...'"

20:28.680 --> 20:30.560
-[ Electricity humming ]
-[ Audience murmuring ]

20:30.560 --> 20:33.400
-HIDDLEDEAN: Oh, dear.
-PRESCOTT: Oh, for God's sake.

20:33.400 --> 20:35.840
HIDDLEDEAN: Stay calm, everyone.
Just stay absolutely calm.

20:35.840 --> 20:36.800
Stay where you are.

20:36.800 --> 20:38.280
All will be well

20:38.280 --> 20:41.600
in -- in an --
in just a tiny second.

20:41.600 --> 20:43.400
-[ Beeping ]
-[ Electricity crackling ]

20:45.200 --> 20:46.800
Let's get to the bar
before it shuts.

20:46.800 --> 20:47.920
-[ Metal sings, thuds ]
-[ Man grunts ]

20:47.920 --> 20:49.120
[ Thud ]

20:49.120 --> 20:50.600
HIDDLEDEAN:
The back-up generator...

20:50.600 --> 20:52.120
-[ Women screaming ]
-MAN: Oh, my God!

20:52.120 --> 20:54.160
[ Indistinct shouting ]

20:55.720 --> 20:57.160
Oh, my God!

20:57.160 --> 20:59.080
[ Indistinct shouting
and screaming ]

20:59.080 --> 21:01.600
Oh, my God!

21:01.600 --> 21:03.600
-Help!
-Somebody help!

21:03.600 --> 21:05.240
Help!

21:05.320 --> 21:07.400
Help!

21:11.840 --> 21:17.920
Precisely six miles, 27 feet,
and eight inches away,

21:17.920 --> 21:21.680
a shiver ran down
Matilda's spine.

21:21.680 --> 21:23.400
She paused to wonder

21:23.400 --> 21:25.000
if the shiver bore
any significance

21:25.000 --> 21:26.680
to the photograph
she was holding

21:26.680 --> 21:28.600
of her missing mother,
Eleanor.

21:28.600 --> 21:30.640
The photograph
had come to replace

21:30.640 --> 21:33.920
the fading memory
of the woman Matilda once knew.

21:33.920 --> 21:35.800
Every day that passed,

21:35.800 --> 21:38.800
Matilda's memory of her mother
became ever weaker.

21:38.800 --> 21:41.240
"One day," thought Matilda...

21:41.240 --> 21:43.840
This photo will be
all I have left.

21:50.200 --> 21:52.360
[ Telephone rings ]

21:54.360 --> 21:56.760
Hello?

21:56.760 --> 21:58.800
Hello?
The phone's ringing.

22:05.680 --> 22:06.840
Sergeant Mati--

22:06.840 --> 22:09.840
I mean, Detective Sergeant
Matilda Stone.

22:09.840 --> 22:12.120
MAN:
There's been a murder.

22:12.120 --> 22:14.000
[ Police radio chatter ]

22:31.400 --> 22:33.960
Dr. Lynch, our local G.P.
and resident pathologist.

22:33.960 --> 22:35.280
Detective Sergeant
Matilda Stone.

22:35.280 --> 22:36.080
Dr. Lynch.

22:36.080 --> 22:37.600
Daniel, please.

22:37.600 --> 22:39.520
[ Wedding bells chiming]

22:41.360 --> 22:44.800
Matilda had never been given
to flights of fancy,

22:44.800 --> 22:47.680
but in that instant,
the possibilities of her life

22:47.680 --> 22:49.360
with Daniel Lynch

22:49.360 --> 22:52.000
scribbled themselves
onto her consciousness

22:52.000 --> 22:54.760
with the perpetuity
of a permanent marker.

22:54.760 --> 22:57.920
JANE: Mattie?

22:57.920 --> 22:59.880
We're here for you.

23:01.200 --> 23:03.640
I don't think
she can see us.

23:03.640 --> 23:05.520
Mattie!

23:05.520 --> 23:07.360
Quite the fan club
you have there.

23:07.360 --> 23:08.160
Shh!

23:08.160 --> 23:09.920
I think she's seen us.

23:09.920 --> 23:11.400
If you could show us the body,
Sergeant.

23:11.400 --> 23:13.080
Yes, sir.

23:19.840 --> 23:21.960
Oscar Prescott, 42, single.

23:21.960 --> 23:23.480
He was on stage
when the attack took place,

23:23.480 --> 23:25.640
but the lights were out,
so no one saw who did it.

23:25.640 --> 23:27.160
Hit from behind.

23:27.160 --> 23:29.320
Killed with a single blow,
by the looks of it.

23:29.320 --> 23:31.840
-How long were the lights out?
-Less than a minute.

23:31.840 --> 23:33.440
So the killer must have
already been on stage

23:33.440 --> 23:35.200
before the lights went out?

23:35.200 --> 23:37.000
-Or in the wings.
-Or in the wings.

23:45.080 --> 23:46.200
Suspects?

23:48.080 --> 23:51.040
Oh! Sorry.
I-I made a list.

23:51.040 --> 23:54.320
Event organizer
Lady Hiddledean.

23:54.320 --> 23:57.240
Oscar's agent, Guy Ashton.

23:57.240 --> 24:00.960
Award nominees Benjamin Kingston
and Isabella Wolfe.

24:00.960 --> 24:03.320
Oscar's P.A., Emily Rose.

24:03.320 --> 24:05.960
His publisher,
Maximilian Sinclair.

24:05.960 --> 24:08.200
Literary agent Tobias Young.

24:08.200 --> 24:09.240
And...

24:11.880 --> 24:13.920
And?

24:13.920 --> 24:15.600
MATILDA:
Award nominee Beth Stone.

24:15.600 --> 24:17.360
Stone?
Any relation?

24:17.360 --> 24:18.480
Her aunt.

24:18.480 --> 24:19.960
Please don't take me
off the case, sir.

24:19.960 --> 24:21.440
I promise I can be impartial.

24:21.440 --> 24:23.040
You better had, Sergeant.

24:23.040 --> 24:25.680
Otherwise your first case in
charge will also be your last.

24:32.800 --> 24:35.560
You can rely on me, sir.
I won't let you down.

24:40.720 --> 24:42.280
[ Laughter ]

24:42.280 --> 24:45.320
No, no, no, no, no, no!
No group hugs!

24:45.320 --> 24:47.160
Inspector Thorne will see.

24:47.160 --> 24:49.680
Oh, come on, kid, give us this.
We haven't seen you for months.

24:49.680 --> 24:51.520
I've made up
your old room ready.

24:51.520 --> 24:53.920
And there's tuna pasta bake
in the fridge.

24:53.920 --> 24:56.520
I expect you want us
to tell you who did it.

24:56.520 --> 24:58.920
-You know?
-We have our theories.

24:58.920 --> 25:00.480
Then keep them to yourselves.

25:00.480 --> 25:02.600
The inspector wants this
investigation done by the book.

25:02.600 --> 25:07.000
That means absolutely
no outside interference.

25:07.000 --> 25:08.200
It also means you, Aunt Beth,

25:08.200 --> 25:09.560
are on my possible list
of suspects.

25:09.560 --> 25:10.760
Me?

25:10.760 --> 25:12.480
I never even
met Oscar Prescott

25:12.480 --> 25:13.600
before this evening.

25:13.600 --> 25:15.520
CAT: You don't seriously
suspect Beth.

25:15.520 --> 25:17.120
MATILDA: Well, you taught me
a good detective

25:17.120 --> 25:18.560
always keeps an open mind.

25:18.560 --> 25:24.000
But, no, of course I don't.
Just don't leave town.

25:26.560 --> 25:28.120
Oh...

25:28.120 --> 25:30.840
Look at her go.
All grown up.

25:32.920 --> 25:34.840
Where did Beth go now?

25:34.840 --> 25:37.440
What?
Oh, I didn't see.

25:37.440 --> 25:39.440
My man Arthur will tell you,

25:39.440 --> 25:42.760
the castle's lighting
predates the war.

25:42.760 --> 25:44.440
They're always going out.

25:44.440 --> 25:45.960
I just can't afford
to get them fixed.

25:45.960 --> 25:47.680
Here's a list of people
I need to interview.

25:47.680 --> 25:48.760
-What?
-I'll need a room.

25:48.760 --> 25:51.400
-Nobody leaves until I say.
-Right.

25:53.040 --> 25:55.360
I think we'll have omelets
for supper.

25:55.360 --> 25:58.440
Arthur?
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

26:03.120 --> 26:05.480
Do you smell smoke?

26:05.480 --> 26:08.280
I haven't been able
to smell anything since 1984.

26:08.280 --> 26:10.160
[ Sniffing ]

26:15.000 --> 26:16.160
Excuse me.

26:16.160 --> 26:18.560
My nerves
are a little on edge today.

26:18.560 --> 26:19.920
Do you have
a spare cigarette?

26:19.920 --> 26:22.480
Sorry, I, uh --
I don't smoke.

26:22.480 --> 26:24.160
Oh.
My mistake.

26:35.960 --> 26:37.840
I'm sure we can spare a moment
if you...

26:37.840 --> 26:40.400
No, no, no.
S-Sorry.

26:42.560 --> 26:46.480
Um, I first met Oscar
20 years ago

26:46.480 --> 26:49.200
at a book signing
for "Apples and Pears."

26:49.200 --> 26:51.400
Oscar's first
Charlie Palmer novel.

26:51.400 --> 26:54.000
I must have read that book
a hundred times.

26:54.000 --> 26:58.160
We hit it off straightaway,
and we stayed in touch.

26:58.160 --> 27:00.120
And when Oscar learned
that I set up

27:00.120 --> 27:01.520
the Charlie Palmer Fan Club,

27:01.520 --> 27:04.520
he asked if I would come
and work for him as his P.A.

27:04.520 --> 27:07.920
And were you
ever anything more?

27:07.920 --> 27:11.240
Is that really necessary,
Sergeant?

27:11.240 --> 27:15.400
My relationship with Oscar
was purely professional.

27:15.400 --> 27:19.160
The only love we shared
was for Charlie Palmer.

27:19.160 --> 27:22.240
And you, Mr. Kingston?

27:22.240 --> 27:24.200
Oscar and I shared rooms
at Cambridge.

27:24.200 --> 27:26.320
We both read English.

27:26.320 --> 27:27.800
And you weren't jealous

27:27.800 --> 27:31.280
that Oscar beat you
to the Golden Pick-Axe Award?

27:31.280 --> 27:33.920
Writing my novel
was an academic exercise.

27:33.920 --> 27:36.560
I care nothing for awards.

27:36.560 --> 27:39.520
Had anything been troubling
Oscar recently?

27:39.520 --> 27:42.600
Did he have any fallings-out
with anyone?

27:44.360 --> 27:46.880
He had a bust-up with his agent
this morning.

27:46.880 --> 27:49.080
-Guy Ashton.
-But it was nothing.

27:49.080 --> 27:51.840
Guy loves Oscar.

27:51.840 --> 27:53.760
He would never hurt him.

27:56.760 --> 27:59.480
Oscar is special.

27:59.480 --> 28:01.960
Was special.

28:01.960 --> 28:03.000
[ Blows nose ]

28:07.320 --> 28:10.280
I discovered him
while he was still at Cambridge,

28:10.280 --> 28:12.800
I secured him
his first publishing deal

28:12.800 --> 28:14.240
when he was there.

28:14.240 --> 28:18.240
I understand you and Oscar
had a falling-out earlier today?

28:18.240 --> 28:20.560
It's part of a ritual dance
we went through

28:20.560 --> 28:22.040
every contract-renewal time.

28:22.040 --> 28:23.760
I -- I offer one thing,

28:23.760 --> 28:27.080
Oscar demands something else,
we -- we fight, we make up,

28:27.080 --> 28:29.640
we agree on something
in the middle.

28:29.640 --> 28:31.680
So Oscar re-signed with you?

28:31.680 --> 28:34.040
It was gonna happen any day.

28:34.040 --> 28:37.960
Look, I would
never hurt Oscar.

28:37.960 --> 28:39.840
He was my greatest find.

28:41.640 --> 28:43.800
My greatest achievement.

28:43.800 --> 28:46.480
[ Knock on door, door opens ]

28:46.480 --> 28:48.840
[ High-pitched ] Come in.
[ Clears throat ] Come in.

28:51.560 --> 28:53.920
Sorry to bother you. There's
something you need to see.

28:56.400 --> 28:59.000
Oscar Prescott's manuscript.
The last pages are missing.

29:05.920 --> 29:07.320
Well, it's already unlocked.

29:14.440 --> 29:16.480
Well, he wasn't much
for keeping things tidy, was he?

29:16.480 --> 29:17.960
Well, help me look
for his laptop.

29:17.960 --> 29:20.680
Oh, you won't find one.
Oscar wrote everything by hand.

29:20.680 --> 29:22.840
-Did he make a copy?
-Never.

29:22.840 --> 29:25.120
He was paranoid someone would
read it before he was ready.

29:25.120 --> 29:26.480
Someone's gone
to a great deal of trouble

29:26.480 --> 29:28.800
to hide the ending
to "Brown Bread."

29:28.800 --> 29:30.600
Solve Charlie Palmer's case,

29:30.600 --> 29:33.360
I'm betting it'll lead us
to whoever killed its author.

29:36.760 --> 29:38.040
[ Bicycle bell dings ]

29:55.600 --> 29:56.600
Sorry.

29:56.600 --> 29:58.720
Beth's always been
more of the cook.

29:58.720 --> 30:00.040
It looks lovely, thanks.

30:00.040 --> 30:01.720
CAT: Hello?

30:01.720 --> 30:03.600
Are you sure it's okay
for me to stay?

30:03.600 --> 30:05.880
'Cause I could get
my own place.

30:05.880 --> 30:08.120
-[ Door closes ]
-And waste money on rent?

30:09.480 --> 30:12.520
-CAT: Morning.
-JANE: Morning.

30:12.520 --> 30:13.960
[ Sighs ]

30:15.840 --> 30:17.640
Oh, coffee.

30:17.640 --> 30:18.640
Morning, Aunt Cat.

30:18.640 --> 30:20.760
Mm...

30:20.760 --> 30:23.000
I told you before,
it's just Cat.

30:23.000 --> 30:24.240
"Aunt" makes me feel old.

30:24.240 --> 30:26.160
Are you eating that?

30:27.720 --> 30:28.840
Go ahead.

30:31.480 --> 30:34.960
So, how's the manuscript?

30:34.960 --> 30:36.240
Well, without the last
five pages,

30:36.240 --> 30:37.320
I haven't a clue
who Charlie Palmer

30:37.320 --> 30:39.080
was about to name
as the murderer.

30:39.080 --> 30:40.720
Well, we could
take a look for you.

30:40.720 --> 30:42.840
I told you yesterday,
butt out.

30:42.840 --> 30:44.360
Inspector Thorne's orders.

30:44.360 --> 30:45.880
Oh!

30:45.880 --> 30:47.600
So I won't ask you
if you think it's odd

30:47.600 --> 30:50.000
that Oscar won the award
in the first place.

30:50.000 --> 30:51.560
Shouldn't he have?

30:51.560 --> 30:53.800
Well, according to
Isabella Wolfe,

30:53.800 --> 30:55.920
Lady H. promised it
to Benjamin Kingston

30:55.920 --> 30:57.640
if he attended the festival.

30:57.640 --> 30:59.320
Sour grapes.

30:59.320 --> 31:01.280
From what I heard, Isabella
and Oscar hated each other.

31:01.280 --> 31:03.400
[ Laughs ]
I'm not so sure.

31:04.600 --> 31:07.120
I saw Oscar
leaving Isabella's room.

31:20.240 --> 31:21.720
And let's just say
they both looked like

31:21.720 --> 31:23.560
they needed a cold shower.

31:29.120 --> 31:31.880
Oh!
I've got to go.

31:31.880 --> 31:33.360
I'll see you at the castle?

31:33.360 --> 31:36.520
Mm, we'll be there,
taking down our stalls.

31:36.520 --> 31:38.640
Minding our own business.

31:40.920 --> 31:42.280
Thanks for breakfast.

31:51.280 --> 31:52.720
[ Door opens ]

31:52.720 --> 31:54.880
All right, out with it.

31:54.880 --> 31:56.680
-[ Door closes ]
-What?

31:56.680 --> 31:59.280
Well, the cleaning is clearly
a displacement activity.

31:59.280 --> 32:00.600
The last time
I saw you like this,

32:00.600 --> 32:01.840
you'd just been dumped
at the altar.

32:03.280 --> 32:05.960
Beth lied to Matilda.

32:10.520 --> 32:12.960
She told Matilda she'd never
even met Oscar Prescott

32:12.960 --> 32:13.760
until last night.

32:13.760 --> 32:15.560
PRESCOTT: Come on.

32:16.720 --> 32:18.520
But I saw her with Oscar
yesterday morning,

32:18.520 --> 32:21.920
and she looked really,
well, angry with him.

32:21.920 --> 32:23.560
[ Speaking indistinctly]

32:23.560 --> 32:25.640
Well, that's your problem.

32:25.640 --> 32:27.160
Oscar!

32:27.160 --> 32:29.560
And, what, now you think
Beth killed Oscar Prescott?

32:29.560 --> 32:31.680
No!

32:31.680 --> 32:33.040
Maybe...

32:34.360 --> 32:37.320
I don't know.
Why would she lie?

32:37.320 --> 32:39.480
And to Matilda, of all people.

32:40.920 --> 32:42.400
There's one way to find out.

32:44.400 --> 32:45.800
Ask her.

33:05.440 --> 33:06.560
Are those the...?

33:06.560 --> 33:08.160
KINGSTON: The missing pages?
Yes.

33:08.160 --> 33:09.640
Did anyone see
who put them there?

33:09.640 --> 33:12.280
No, they were like this
when we came down for breakfast.

33:12.280 --> 33:15.360
The murderer is...

33:20.480 --> 33:21.480
Baron Tollage.

33:23.360 --> 33:24.600
You naughty boy.

33:24.600 --> 33:26.560
Baron Tollage?

33:28.760 --> 33:30.960
That doesn't make sense.

33:32.560 --> 33:34.160
Maybe whoever stole them
was so scared

33:34.160 --> 33:35.880
of being implicated
in the murders

33:35.880 --> 33:37.200
they decided to return them.

33:37.200 --> 33:39.640
Or they're not
the real pages.

33:39.640 --> 33:41.080
No, they're genuine.

33:41.080 --> 33:42.920
How can you be so sure?

33:42.920 --> 33:45.520
I have a PhD in stylometry.

33:45.520 --> 33:47.960
It's the study
of linguistic styles

33:47.960 --> 33:50.080
used to attribute authorship.

33:50.080 --> 33:53.880
Every author's writing style
is unique,

33:53.880 --> 33:56.080
like a fingerprint.

33:57.840 --> 34:00.160
I'd know Oscar's anywhere.

34:09.800 --> 34:12.199
Beth?
Open up. It's us.

34:12.199 --> 34:14.159
She is not answering
her mobile.

34:16.560 --> 34:17.880
Beth!

34:17.880 --> 34:19.920
You don't think Beth
had anything to do

34:19.920 --> 34:21.560
with Oscar's death, do you?

34:21.560 --> 34:22.880
Not without good reason.

34:22.880 --> 34:24.880
Well, what does that mean?

34:24.880 --> 34:26.560
It means it's time
we got involved.

34:26.560 --> 34:28.480
Matilda told us not to.

34:28.480 --> 34:30.639
That was before
it became personal.

34:30.639 --> 34:32.480
So, what are you going to do?

34:32.480 --> 34:33.960
Find out why Isabella Wolfe

34:33.960 --> 34:35.600
lied about her relationship
with Oscar.

34:35.600 --> 34:38.280
What am I supposed to do?

34:38.280 --> 34:40.639
Well, follow up your suspicions
about Max Sinclair.

34:40.639 --> 34:43.120
-What suspicions?
-Asking for a cigarette?

34:43.120 --> 34:45.239
You've never smoked
in your life.

34:45.239 --> 34:47.639
I was surprised to smell smoke
on him, that's all.

34:49.120 --> 34:49.960
[ Sniffing]

34:50.960 --> 34:52.239
Ash marks.

34:56.800 --> 34:59.520
Oh, you think Max Sinclair was
lying about not being a smoker?

34:59.520 --> 35:02.040
No, I think he'd been
standing near a fire.

35:02.040 --> 35:03.800
In the middle of summer?

35:23.840 --> 35:25.200
[ Dings ]

35:25.200 --> 35:27.040
I'm looking
for Isabella Wolfe.

35:27.040 --> 35:29.120
She's gone into Wildemarsh.

35:29.120 --> 35:30.600
The paintings and photographs

35:30.600 --> 35:32.720
that hung in the corridor
yesterday, where...?

35:35.080 --> 35:37.880
They've been sent to Wildemarsh
Antiques for restoration.

35:44.080 --> 35:45.720
While Matilda was pondering

35:45.720 --> 35:49.320
Lady Hiddledean's liberal use
of her limited funds...

35:54.040 --> 35:56.320
...Cat Stone was pondering

35:56.320 --> 36:00.360
Isabella Wolfe's equally
liberal use of alcohol...

36:00.360 --> 36:01.680
[ Sighs ]

36:04.440 --> 36:07.600
...and asking herself
if it was in any way connected

36:07.600 --> 36:10.400
to the recent death
of a young woman

36:10.400 --> 36:13.040
called Sadie Hanson.

36:15.400 --> 36:17.840
All I'm asking for is 40%.

36:17.840 --> 36:19.000
Give me a minute, would you?

36:21.480 --> 36:22.960
YOUNG:
It's just an advance.

36:22.960 --> 36:25.520
Mr. Sinclair, Mr. Young,

36:25.520 --> 36:27.040
I need to ask you
a few questions.

36:27.040 --> 36:28.440
Can this wait?

36:28.440 --> 36:30.200
We're in the middle
of a negotiation here.

36:30.200 --> 36:32.160
SINCLAIR:
Excuse my colleague, Sergeant.

36:32.160 --> 36:33.280
Ask away.

36:33.280 --> 36:35.080
Although I'm the last person

36:35.080 --> 36:36.760
that would want
poor Oscar dead.

36:36.760 --> 36:38.600
And why would that be?

36:38.600 --> 36:41.040
He made me a rich man.

36:41.040 --> 36:43.560
I took a gamble
publishing "Apples and Pears,"

36:43.560 --> 36:47.200
but it was an instant hit, like
every Charlie Palmer book since.

36:47.200 --> 36:51.400
Killing Oscar would be like
killing the golden goose.

36:53.680 --> 36:55.840
-And you?
-Well, Oscar was my client.

36:55.840 --> 36:57.320
Why would I want him dead?

36:57.320 --> 36:59.680
I understood Oscar was signed
to Guy Ashton.

36:59.680 --> 37:01.160
Yes, he was.

37:02.920 --> 37:04.160
Till yesterday.

37:08.600 --> 37:10.000
[ Door unlocks ]

37:13.920 --> 37:17.920
Meanwhile, Jane Stone
was congratulating herself

37:17.920 --> 37:18.800
on her foresight...

37:18.800 --> 37:20.040
[ Sniffs ]

37:20.040 --> 37:21.480
...having recently completed

37:21.480 --> 37:24.920
the university of hard knocks's
ever-popular

37:24.920 --> 37:28.120
"how to pick any lock"
correspondence course...

37:37.880 --> 37:41.800
...while in her flat above
Wildemarsh Auto Body Repairs,

37:41.800 --> 37:45.480
Jane's sister Cat had picked
a more modern

37:45.480 --> 37:49.080
and somewhat less criminal
method of investigation.

38:06.480 --> 38:10.080
No, Oscar would never leave me
for a charlatan

38:10.080 --> 38:11.800
like Tobias Young.

38:13.400 --> 38:16.080
But he does have
Oscar's signature on a contract.

38:25.360 --> 38:28.400
Well, this is fake.
It has to be.

38:28.400 --> 38:30.440
As you can see,
the signature was witnessed.

38:35.200 --> 38:37.200
I -- I-I was
going to tell you.

38:37.200 --> 38:38.360
That snake!

38:41.520 --> 38:42.640
This doesn't end here.

38:42.640 --> 38:44.200
Guy.

38:44.280 --> 38:45.560
Guy?

38:45.560 --> 38:46.880
-Just stay there.
-[ Door opens, closes ]

38:46.880 --> 38:49.600
[ Cellphone rings ]

38:49.600 --> 38:50.920
Detective Stone.

38:50.920 --> 38:52.240
There's a woman
causing a disturbance

38:52.240 --> 38:53.640
at The Embittered Hack.

38:53.640 --> 38:55.720
I'm a bit tied up
at the moment, Terry.

38:55.720 --> 38:57.960
Yeah, but it sounds like
Isabella Wolfe.

39:01.840 --> 39:03.000
If you could wait here.

39:05.040 --> 39:06.080
[ Door opens ]

39:11.600 --> 39:14.320
Get your hands off me!

39:14.320 --> 39:15.720
Don't come back.

39:15.720 --> 39:18.960
I wouldn't step back
in that dump if you paid me!

39:21.200 --> 39:22.600
Isabella.

39:22.600 --> 39:24.080
Oh, it's you.

39:24.080 --> 39:25.720
-What do you want?
-We need to talk.

39:25.720 --> 39:26.800
What about?

39:26.800 --> 39:28.520
Oscar Prescott being seen
leaving your room

39:28.520 --> 39:29.480
yesterday afternoon.

39:36.560 --> 39:38.960
-Here.
-Cheers.

39:41.280 --> 39:42.960
MATILDA: So?

39:45.480 --> 39:47.560
Oscar and I were lovers.

39:49.840 --> 39:51.960
There, I've said it.

39:51.960 --> 39:54.360
-And the whole animosity thing?
-A cover.

39:54.360 --> 39:56.840
Oscar didn't want
anyone to know.

39:56.840 --> 40:00.120
Bad for his image, he said.

40:00.120 --> 40:01.760
You're barking
up the wrong tree

40:01.760 --> 40:04.360
if you think I had
anything to do with his death.

40:04.360 --> 40:06.960
You need to start
looking closer to home.

40:06.960 --> 40:08.640
Meaning?

40:08.640 --> 40:12.760
Your Aunt Beth isn't the saint
you think she is.

40:14.400 --> 40:17.720
I heard her tell you
she didn't know Oscar.

40:17.720 --> 40:22.320
But I saw them arguing
yesterday morning.

40:23.760 --> 40:25.000
Oscar!

40:27.240 --> 40:30.040
[ Shouting indistinctly]

40:39.480 --> 40:42.760
Despite learning
of her Aunt Beth's deceit,

40:42.760 --> 40:46.280
and for reasons
she had yet to fathom,

40:46.280 --> 40:49.240
Matilda's thoughts
kept returning to the one woman

40:49.240 --> 40:52.400
she had trusted
above all others...

40:54.480 --> 40:57.320
...her missing mother,
Eleanor.

41:04.680 --> 41:08.280
Meanwhile, Matilda's Aunt Cat
chose a deception

41:08.280 --> 41:10.200
of a very different kind.

41:13.480 --> 41:16.400
-Sadie Hanson's landlord?
-Yeah?

41:16.400 --> 41:18.720
I'm a reporter
for the Wildemarsh Watchman.

41:18.720 --> 41:20.200
I need to see her room.

41:42.840 --> 41:45.080
So Sadie knew Oscar.

41:59.080 --> 42:01.600
200 on Black Blaze to win.
You know I'm good for it.

42:01.600 --> 42:03.120
-[ Cellphone chimes ]
-Hold on.

42:06.600 --> 42:11.040
While Tobias Young
figured out his options,

42:11.040 --> 42:13.960
Jane Stone was busily engaged
in figures

42:13.960 --> 42:15.600
of a rather different nature.

42:32.000 --> 42:34.520
[ Dog barking in distance ]

42:34.520 --> 42:37.040
Aunt Beth?

42:37.040 --> 42:40.040
I really need to speak to you
about Oscar Prescott.

42:46.160 --> 42:49.400
But Aunt Beth didn't want
to speak to Matilda,

42:49.400 --> 42:52.040
and Matilda was left
to wonder why,

42:52.040 --> 42:54.000
of all the people in the world,

42:54.000 --> 42:57.560
her Aunt Beth would choose
to lie to her.

42:59.760 --> 43:02.880
And while Matilda
concerned herself with a lie,

43:02.880 --> 43:05.280
Cat Stone
was about to be reminded

43:05.280 --> 43:06.840
of a universal truth...

43:09.520 --> 43:12.440
...namely that
good artists copy

43:12.440 --> 43:15.440
but great artists steal.

43:43.640 --> 43:46.520
Although still blessed with
good health and good looks...

43:46.520 --> 43:48.000
Hello?

43:48.000 --> 43:50.360
...literary agent Tobias Young

43:50.360 --> 43:53.080
continued to have
considerably less luck

43:53.080 --> 43:55.520
in other areas of his life...

43:55.520 --> 43:58.360
Anybody here?

43:58.360 --> 44:00.960
...luck that,
if nothing else...

44:02.400 --> 44:04.360
...was at least consistent.

44:04.360 --> 44:06.320
Pbbbbbt.

44:06.320 --> 44:08.280
[ Creaking ]

44:18.440 --> 44:19.600
[ Thud ]

44:21.320 --> 44:22.840
[ Crashing ]
